{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"245baa8a-f9d3-4909-9c20-ab2ed39b7061","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform tool for .NET performance tracing.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU trace (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or convert to `.speedscope` format:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\nThen open it at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n### Alternative: PerfView\nFor deeper OS-level analysis (kernel + managed stacks), use **PerfView**:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for simplicity. Escalate to PerfView if you need kernel-level detail (I/O, thread contention, etc.).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f254741e-8346-4880-b67f-e843825691e4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question — no code changes or repo exploration needed. I'll give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":380,"requestId":"6003:3E203F:274D00:2EBB75:69EAC5C9"},"id":"63531ee8-0756-458b-a91d-8d7837c05b36","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:22:28.661Z","parentId":"c2f08f61-e885-4030-a88e-47c9a1ac754e"}
